<DOC><DOCNO> AP891102-0186 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-89 1940EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-02 0346</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0359</SECOND><HEAD>Snow Closes Schools in Parts of Michigan, Wisconsin</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy snow shut down schools and businesses in parts of Michiganand northern Wisconsin on Thursday, while rain plagued theSoutheast.   Michigan's western Upper Peninsula was covered in up to 36inches of snow that had fallen since Tuesday. Snow-plowing crewswere forced off the streets Thursday by too much snow and ice.   The snow snarled traffic, but no serious accidents or injurieswere reported.   Scattered electrical outages were reported in Ironwood, Mich.Four public school districts shut down, along with Gogebic Countybuses and some businesses in Ironwood, sheriff's Deputy Jay Kangassaid.   Far northern Wisconsin got two feet of snow since Wednesday.   ``They (residents) don't like it, but they're used to it,'' saidLarry Baldovin, sheriff in Iron County, Wis.   Geri Zaelski, a bookkeeper for Hurley, Wis., Public Schools,struggled through hip-deep drifts to get to work even thoughschools were closed.   ``I live only two blocks from work and I had too much work to doto miss a whole day,'' she said.   The snow was attributed to low pressure over Lake Huron.   Light snow was scattered across the upper Mississippi Valley,eastern portions of the Dakotas and the Minneapolis area ofMinnesota.   Rainshowers ahead of a cold front in the Southeast werescattered from the central Gulf Coast to Georgia and South Carolina.   Cloudy skies prevailed from the Mississippi Valley to theAtlantic Coast and from the Dakotas to Washington, with sunny skiesacross much of the rest of the nation.   Temperatures dipped below freezing in the Great Plains region,with single-digit readings as far south as southeast Colorado.   Highs in Florida were in the 70s and 80s, with temperatuers inthe 60s in the Gulf Coast.   A new record low for the date _ 22 degrees _ was set in Midland,Texas. The old record, set in 1966, was 27 degrees.   The morning cold spots in the Lower 48 states were Grand Forks,N.D., and Yellowstone National Park, Wyo. Both had lows of 4degrees.</TEXT></DOC>